So first I will do angle bisector theorem and get the lengths of BD and CD. While using the Pythagorean theorem find what AD is. Knowing that AD, AB, and BD form a triangle, use the law of cosine to compute angle BAD: <answer> $BD = \frac{48}{7}, CD = \frac{32}{7}$
Using the Pythagorean theorem to get AD starts to look ugly so I set $$\begin{aligned}

&BC^2 = BD^2 + DC^2 - 2(BD)(DC)\cos \angle BDC \\
\implies BDC \cos \angle BDC &= \frac(BD^2 + DC^2 - BC^2)}{2(BD)(DC)}

\end{aligned}$$
with $BC=8$, $BD=\frac{32}{7}D$, $DC = \frac{48}{7}D$ we obtain
\begin{aligned}

\cos \angle BDC &= \frac(\frac{BD^2+DC^2-BC^2}{2(BD)(DC)}\\
&= \frac(AB^2+AD^2-BD^2 - (AC^2 + AD^2 - DC^2)}{4BD \cdot DC}
\end{aligned}
$$\begin{aligned}

&D \cos \angle BAD = \frac(AB^2+AC^2 - BD^2 - DC^2)}{4 \cdot BD \cdot DC}\\
\implies \cos^2 \angle BAD &= \frac(AB^2+AC^2-BD^2 - DC^2)^2}{16 \cdot BD^2 \cdot DC^2}

\end{aligned}$$
Utilizing $AB=3$, $AC=6$,$BD = \frac{48}{7}$,$DC = \frac{32}{7}$ we can arrive at
$$\begin{aligned}

\cos^2 \angle BAD &= \frac(\frac{(3^2 + 6^2) - (\frac{48}{7})^2 - (\frac{32}{7})^2}{16 \cdot (\frac{32}{7})^2 \cdot (\frac{48}{7})^2})\\
\implies \cos \angle BAD &= (\frac{(81 + 144) - (2 \cdot 32 \cdot 48) + 2 \cdot 32 \cdot 48)}{16 (32)(48)}) \to (\frac{225}{16(32)(48)})
\end{aligned}$$
$$\begin{aligned}

\cos \angle BAD &= \boxed(\frac{25}{256})
\end{aligned}$$
Answer: \boxed(\frac{25}{256})}
